---
title: 01 bits, bytes, shifts
---

Q: What is the signed value of an n-bit two's-complement pattern `u`?
A: `u` if `u < 2^(n-1)`, else `u - 2^n`.

---

Q: What is two's-complement negation as bit operations?
A: Flip every bit, then add one: `-x == ~x + 1` at fixed width.

---

Q: What is Python `~x` arithmetically?
A: `~x == -x - 1`; mask afterward when emulating fixed width.

---

Q: Which Python operations need a mask afterward for u32/u64 emulation?
A: `+`, `-`, `*`, `<<`, `~`, and unary `-`.

---

Q: How do you logical-right-shift a possibly-negative Python value as u32?
A: `(x & 0xffffffff) >> n`.

---

Q: Test, set, clear, and toggle bit `k`.
A: Test `(x >> k) & 1`; set `x | (1 << k)`; clear `x & ~(1 << k)`; toggle `x ^ (1 << k)`.

---

Q: Extract a bit field at `offset` of `width`.
A: `(word >> offset) & ((1 << width) - 1)`.

---

Q: Insert `value` into a bit field.
A: `(word & ~(mask << offset)) | ((value & mask) << offset)`, where `mask = (1 << width) - 1`.

---

Q: What does `x & -x` do?
A: Isolates the lowest set bit.

---

Q: What does `x & (x - 1)` do?
A: Clears the lowest set bit.

---

Q: What is the correct power-of-two test?
A: `x != 0 and (x & (x - 1)) == 0`.

---

Q: Why does the naked power-of-two test accept zero?
A: Because `0 & (0 - 1) == 0`.

---

Q: Python one-liner for next power of two for `x >= 1`?
A: `1 << (x - 1).bit_length()`.

---

Q: What is `-7 >> 1`, and why is it not C `-7 / 2`?
A: `-4`; arithmetic shift floors, while C integer division truncates toward zero.

---

Q: Why is `(1 << 31)` undefined in C on 32-bit `int`?
A: `1` is signed `int`; shifting into the sign bit overflows. Use `1u << 31`.

---

Q: What is the submask enumeration update?
A: `s = (s - 1) & m`, with an explicit break after visiting `0`.

---

Q: What is `reverse_bits32(1)`?
A: `0x80000000`.

---

Q: What is the fastest Python popcount?
A: `x.bit_count()`.
